  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Integrated WASH Response for IDPs and Vulnerable Host Communities in Badghis Province</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">WV Afghanistan (WVA) is planning to conduct critical, life-saving interventions under this submission, focusing on WASH in Badghis Province in order to reduce the incidence of diarrhea-related malnutrition in children under 5. These interventions will contribute to Humanitarian Response Plan outcomes 1: Save lives in areas of highest need.

WVA will implement WASH activities including provision of life-saving safe drinking water, sanitation and hygiene services for conflict-affected IDPs and vulnerable host communities in Qala-I-Naw, Qadis and Ab Kamari districts in Badghis Province in order to reduce the incidence of diarrhea among children under 5. According to the HRP, Badghis is one of the top five provinces in need of such interventions, hosting the third highest level of IDPs. The project will rehabilitate existing water infrastructure and construct new water systems in locations with deeper groundwater to provide IDPs and underserved host communities in 25 target locations with access to life-saving clean drinking water. Water systems, latrine blocks and hand washing stations in 11 schools and one health care facility serving IDP populations will also be rehabilitated. Emergency latrines will be provided to newly arrived IDPs, as identified through a HEAT assessment, from WASH Cluster stock. Positive hygiene practices will also be promoted through trained WASH groups and newly arrived IDPs will be provided with hygiene kits from WASH Cluster stock, as identified through a HEAT assessment. The anticipated decreased rate of diarrhea from WASH interventions will contribute to 2018 HRP WASH Cluster outcome: &#x201C;WASH-related communicable diseases are reduced among IDP, returnee, refugee and non-displaced conflict-affected women, men and children of all ages through timely and adequate WASH assistance.</narrative>
  </description>
